Taux de calcification

# packages
SciViews::R
library(knitr)
source("../../R/function.R")
# dataset
at <-  read("../../data/alcalinity.rds")
nubbins <- read("../../data/nubbins.rds")
growth <- read("../../data/growth.rds") %>.%
  filter(., number_day == 32) %>.%
  select(., localisation, id, skeleton_weight)
nubbins <- left_join(nubbins, growth, by = c("localisation", "id"))
Column `localisation` joining character vector and factor, coercing into character vectorColumn `id` joining factors with different levels, coercing to character vector
at$localisation[at$respi %in% c("A0", "R1", "R2")] <- "control"
Unknown or uninitialised column: 'localisation'.
at$localisation[at$respi %in% c("A1", "R3", "R4", "R5")] <- "hyposalin"
at$localisation[at$respi %in% c("A2", "R6", "R7", "R8")] <- "hypersalin"
# data subset
at %>.%
  filter(.,  !is.na(condi)) -> at_respi

Analyse graphique

Ce premier graphique permet de montrer que lalcalnit est fortement modifie du changement de salinit.

Si lon sintresse uniquement au conditon sans lexprience de respiromtrie, on obtient le graphique ci-dessous.

at%>.%
  filter(., is.na(condi)) %>.%
  pc_plot(data = ., y = "at", x = "number_day", factor = "localisation",
          rect_start = 29.83 + 0:6, rect_end = (29.83 + 0:6) + 0.5) +
  geom_rect(ymin = -Inf, ymax = Inf, xmin = 29.88, xmax = 30.38, alpha = 0.002) +
  labs(y = (expression(
    paste("Alcalinit")~ paste("(mmol.kg"^{ "-1"})~ paste(")"))), 
       color = "Conditions")

Calculons labsorptions : - le respiromtre 8 est truff derreur dencodage et nest donc aucunement utilisable.

at_respi %>.%
  group_by(., condi, localisation) %>.%
  summarise(., mean = mean(at), sd = sd(at), count = sum(!is.na(at)))
chart(at_respi, at ~ number_day %col=% condi | respi) +
  geom_point()

at_respi %>.%
  arrange(., sampledate) %>.%
  mutate(., nb_round = number_day %/%1) %>.%
  filter(., respi != "R8") -> at_respi
 
chart(at_respi, at ~ number_day %col=% condi | respi) +
  geom_point()

Calculons maintenant lassimilation

at_respi %>.%
  arrange(., sampledate) %>.%
  group_by(., respi) %>.%
  mutate(., at_lead = lead(at), 
         at_diff = at-at_lead) %>.%
  filter(., condi != "F") -> at_respi
chart(at_respi, at_diff ~ number_day  | localisation) +
  geom_point()

at_respi %>.%
  group_by(., localisation, period) %>.%
  summarise(., mean = round(mean(calc_rate),2), sd = round(sd(calc_rate),2)) %>.%
  unite(., "mean_sd", c(mean, sd), sep = "+/-") %>.%
  spread(., key = period, value = mean_sd) %>.%
  kable(.,  col.names = c("Conditions", "Taux calcification moyen (jour)", "Taux calcification moyen (nuit)"),caption = "Taux de calcification ( cart-type) pour les diffrentes conditions exprimentales. \\label{tab_calc}")
Conditions Taux calcification moyen (jour) Taux calcification moyen (nuit)
control 3.79+/-1.72 2.86+/-1.46
hypersalin 1.51+/-1.12 1.23+/-0.65
hyposalin 2.55+/-1.68 2.41+/-1.48

Analyse statistique

bartlett.test(mean_respi ~ condition, data = at_red)


    Bartlett test of homogeneity of variances

data:  mean_respi by condition
Bartlett's K-squared = 2.2918, df = 2, p-value = 0.3179

On obtient donc en conclusion une diffrence significative entre le control et le traitement hypersalin.
